it would be a mistake to write to liege for forks and to pay for gloves
miss dahlia derek in your place i would call myself rosa
a flower should smell sweet and woman should have wit
i say nothing of fantine she is a dreamer amusing thoughtful pensive person she is a phantom possessed of the form of a nymph and the modesty of a nun who has strayed into the life of an rosette but who takes refuge in illusions and who sings and prays and gazes into the azure without very well knowing what she sees or what she is doing and who with her eyes fixed in heaven wanders in a garden where there are more birds than are in existence
if anyone know thus it holon yes i am all illusion but she does not even hear me that blond hair of chimeras
as for the rest everything about her is freshness suavity youth sweet morning light
if anyone maid worthy of being called marguerite of pearl you are a woman from the beauteous orient
ladies a second piece of advice do not marry marriage is a graft it takes well or ill avoid that risk
but bag
what am i saying
i am wasting my words
girls are incurable on the subject of marriage and all that we wise men can say will not prevent the waistcoat makers and the shoe stitchers from dreaming of husbands studded with diamonds
well done it but my beauties remember this you eat too much sugar
you have but one fault i woman and that is nibbling sugar
o nibbling sexy our pretty little white teeth adore sugar
now need me well sugar is a salt
all salts are withering
sugar is the most desiccating of all salts it sucks the liquids of the blood through the veins hence the coagulation and then the solidification of the blood hence tubercles in the lungs hence death
that is why diabetes borders on consumption
then do not crunch sugar and you will live
i turn to the man gentlemen make conquest rob each other of your wellbeloved without remorse
