still he felt that he had lost time
night had fully come
they turned into the crossroad the way became frightfully had the cart lurched from one but to the other he said to the postilion keep at a trot and you shall have a double fee
in one of the jolts the shuffle free broke
he replied have you a bit of rope and a knife
yes sir
he cut a branch from a tree and made a whiff letter of it
this caused another loss of twenty minutes but they set out against a gallop
the plain was gloomy low hanging black crisp dogs crept over the hills and wrenched themselves away like smoke there were whitish gleams in the clouds a strong breeze which blew in from the sea produced a sound on all quarters of the horizon as of someone moving furniture everything that could be seen assumed attitudes of terror
how many things shiver beneath these vast breaths of the night
he was stiff with cold he had eaten nothing since the night before he vaguely recalled his other nocturnal trio in the vast plain in the neighborhood of weight years previously and it seemed but yesterday
the hours truck from a distant tower he asked the boy what time is in
the postilion whipped up the horses they had crossed the river and left mont sainte lot behind them
the night grew more profound
chapter vi sisters in plist put to the proof but at that moment fantine was joyous
she had passed a very bad night her cough was frightful here ever had doubled in intensity she had had dreams in the morning when the doctor paid his visits he was delirious he assumed an alarmed look and ordered that he should be informed as soon as m
madeleine arrived
all the morning she was melancholy said but little and laid plaits in her sheets murmuring the while in a low voice calculations which seemed to be calculations of distances
her eyes were hollow and sharing
they seemed almost extinguished at intervals then lighted up again and shone like stars
it seems as though at the approach of a certain darkhour the light of heaven fills those who are quitting the light of earth
each time that sisters implode asked her how she felt she replied invariably well
i should like to seek
madeleine
some months before this at the moment when fantine had just lost her last modesty her last shame and her last joy she was the shadow of herself now she was the spectre of herself
physical suffering had completed the work of moral suffering
this creature office and twenty had a wrinkled brow flabby cheeks pinched nostrils teeth from which the fund had receded a leaden complexion agony neck prominent shoulder blades trail limbs a clayey skin and her golden hair was growing out sprinkled with gray
slac
how illness improvised old age
at midday the physician returned have some directions inquired whether the mayor had made his appearance at the infirmary and shook his head
m
as exactness is kindness he was exact
about half past two fantine began to be restless
in the course of twenty minutes she asked them in more than ten times what time is it sister
at the third strike fantine say join beds he who could in general hardly turnover joined her yellow fleshless hands in a sort of convulsive clasp and the bug heard her utter one of those profound signs which seem to throw off rejection
then can tune turner and looked at the door
no one entered the door did not open
she remained this for a quarter of an hour her eyes riveted on the door motionless and apparently holding her breath
the sister dared not speak to her
the clock struck a quarter past three
f anyone fell back on her pillow
she said nothing but began to plait the sheets once more
half an hour passed then an hour no one came every time the clock struck fan time started up and looked towards the door then fell back again
her thought was clearly perceptible but she uttered noname she made no complaints he blamed no one
but she counted in a melancholy way
one would have said that something dark was descending upon her
she was livid and her lips were blue
she smiled now and then
then the sister heard here at very low and gently he is wrong not to come today since i am going away tomorrow
sisters implode herself was surprised at m
in the meantime fantine was staring at the tester of her bed
she seemed to be endeavoring to recall something
all at once she began to sign in a voice as feeble as a breath
thehun listener
this is what fantine was singing lovely things we will buy a sweet roll the faubourg s through
roses are pink cornflowers are blue i love my love cornflowers are blue
haste to the city buy linen buy a needle buy thread
dear holy virgin beside my stove i have set a cradle with ribbons decker
god may give me his loveliest star i prefer the child thou hast granted me
make of it soiling not spoiling not a petticoat fair with its bodice fine which i will embroider and fill with flowers
this song was an old cradle romance with which she had in former days pulled her little cosette to sleep and which had never recurred to her mind in all the five years during which she had been parted from her child
she sang it in so sad a voice and to so sweet an air that it was enough to make anyone even a gundeep
the sister accustomed as she was to austerities felt a year spring to her eyes
the clock struck six
fantine did not seem to hear it
she no longer seemed to pay attention to anything about her
