man eur
very rarely however twice a month at most
he often spent half a day in gazing at a marketgarden the beds of lettuce the chickens on the dung heap the horse turning the water wheel
the passers by stared at him instr pride and some of them though this attire suspicious and his mnem sinister
he was only a poor young man dreaming in an object less way
it was during one of his strolls that he had hit upon the gorge zu house and tempted by its isolation and its cheapness had taken up his abode there
he was known there only under the name of m
marius
marius had not refused their invitations
they afforded opportunities of talking about his father
thus he went from time to time to comte paull to general bell avec nero general tridion to the invalides
there was music and dancing there
on such evenings marius put on his new coat
but he never went to these evening parties or balls except on days when it was free sign cold because he could not afford a carriage and he did not wish to arrive with boots otherwise than like mirrors
he said sometimes but without bitterness men are so made that in a drawing room you may be a oiled everywhere except on your store
in order to insure a good reception there only one irreproachable thing is asked if you your conscience
nk your boots
all passions except those of the heart are dissipated by revert
the revolution of assisted in the process by satisfying and calming him
he remained the same setting aside his fits of wrath
he still held the same opinions
only they had been tempered
to speak accurately he had no longer any opinions he had sympathies
to what party did he belong
to the party of humanity
out of humanity he chose france out of the nation he chose the people out of the people he chose the woman
it was to that point above all that his pity was directed
now he preferred an idea to a feeds post to a hero and he admired a book like job more than an event like marengo
and then when after a day spent in meditation he returned in the evening through the boulevards and caught a glimpse through the branches of the trees of the fathomless space beyond the nameless gleams the abyss the shadow the mystery all that which is only human seemed very petty indeed to him
he thought that he had and he really had in fact arrived at the truth of life and of human philosophy and he had ended by gazing at nothing but heaven the only thing which truth can perceive from the bottom of her well
this did not prevent him from multiplying his plans his combinations his scaffolding show projects for the future
in fact had it been given to our eyes of the flesh to gaze into the consciences of others we should be able to judge a man much more surely according to what he dreams than according to what he thinks
there is fill in thought there is none in dreams
r every which is utterly spontaneous takes and keeps even in the gigantic and the ideal the form of our spirit
nothing proceeds more directly and more sincerely from the very depth of our soul than our unpremeditated and boundless aspirations towards the splendors of destiny
in these aspirations much more than in deliberate rational coordinated ideas is the real character of a man to be found
our chimeras are the things which the most resemble us
each one of us dreams of the unknown and the impossible in accordance with his nature
towards the middle of this year the old woman who waited on marius told him that his neighbors the wretched jon dee the family had been turned out of doors
marius who passed nearly the whole of his days out of the house hardly knew that he had any neighbors
why are they turned out
he asked
because they do not pay their rent they owe for two quarters
how much is it
twenty france said the old woman
marius had thirty france saved up in a drawer
here he said to the old woman take these twenty five france
pay for the poor people and give them five feet cs and do not tell them that it was i
