chapter xiii solus cum solo un poco de moto non do not a guntur or are paternoster marius dreamer as he was was as we have said firm and energetic by nature
his habits of solitary meditation while they had developed in him sympathy and compassion had perhaps diminished the faculty for irrigation but had left intact the power of waxing indignant he had the kindliness of a brahmin and the severity of a judge he took pity upon a road but he crushed a viper
now it was into a hole of vipers that his glance had just been directed it was a nest of monsters that he had beneath his eyes
these wretches must be stamped upon said he
not one of the enigmas which he had hoped to see solved had been elucidated in the contrary all of them had been rendered more at her if anything he knew nothing more about the beautiful maiden of the luxembourg and the man whom he called m
leblanc except that monde et he was acquainted with the n
athwart the mysterious words which had been uttered the only thing on which he caught a distinct vii move was the fact that an ambush was in course of preparations dark but terrible trap that both of them were incurring great danger she probably her father certainly that they must be saved that the hideous plots of the job fretted must be thwarted and the web of these spiders broken
he scanned the female jon frette for a moment
she had pulled an old sheet iron stove from a corner and she was rummaging among the old heap of iron
he descended from the commode as softly as possible taking care not to make the least noise
amid his terror as to what was in preparation and in the horror with which the kind refresh as inspired him he experienced a sort of joy at the idea that it might be granted to him pst maps to render a service to the one whom he loved
but how was it to be done
how warn the persons threatened
he did not know their address
they had reappeared for an instant before his eyes and had them plunged back again into the immense depths of paris
should be wait form
bution frette and his men would see him on the watch the spot was lonely they were stronger than me they would device means to seize him or to get him away and the man whom marius was anxious to save would be lost
marius had five hours before him
there was but one thing to be done
he put on his decent coat knotted a silk handkerchief round his neck took his hat and went out without making any more noise than if he had been treading on moss with bare feet
moreover the jon dee the women continued to rummage among her old iron
once outside of the house he made for the rue du petit ban quiet
he had almost reached the middle of this street near a very low wall which a man can easily step over at certain points and which abuts on a waste space and was walking slowly in consequence of his preoccupied condition and the snow deadened the sound of his steps all at once he heard voices talking very close by
he turned his head the street was deserted there was not a soul i got it was broad daylight and yet he distinctly heard voices
it occurred to him to glance over the wall which he was skirting
there in fact sat two men flat on the snow with their backs against the wall talking together in subdued tones
these two persons were strangers to him one was a bearded man in a blouse and the other a long haired individual in rags
by thrusting his head over the wall marius could hear their remarks
do you think so
said the bearded man
then they began to discuss a melodrama that they had seen on the preceding evening at the tao te theatre
marius went his way
that must be the affair
he directed his course towards the faubourg saint marceau and asked at the first stop he came to where he could find a commissary of police
he was directed to rue de pontoise no
thither marius betook himself
on the way he rendered justice to providence
be reflected that had he not given his five france to the kind betts girl in the morning he would have followed m
leblanc would have been lost and his daughter with him no doubt
